    "Bottom Line": "Lung-volume–reduction surgery does not provide an overall survival advantage over medical therapy for patients with severe emphysema. However, it increases the chance of improved exercise capacity. A survival benefit is evident in patients with predominantly upper-lobe emphysema and low baseline exercise capacity, while patients classified as high-risk or those with non–upper-lobe emphysema and high exercise capacity are less ideal candidates for surgery due to higher mortality rates and minimal functional gain.",
    "Major Points": "The National Emphysema Treatment Trial (NETT) assessed the impact of lung-volume–reduction surgery on individuals with severe emphysema. The study identified particular subgroups based on emphysema distribution and baseline exercise capacity that could predict differential outcomes from surgery. Patients with upper-lobe emphysema and low exercise capacity experienced a mortality benefit, while those with non-upper-lobe emphysema and high exercise capacity faced increased mortality with negligible improvement following surgery.",
    "Guidelines": "The findings of NETT have likely informed practice guidelines, though specific current guidelines reflecting these results are not detailed in this summary.",
